messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path:
- /printshops/{printShopID}/employees

All HTTP methods acceptable:
- false

Acceptable methods (based on the code):
- HEAD: false
- POST: true
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: true
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

Explanation:
- The addEmployee method is annotated with @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{printShopID}/employees", method = RequestMethod.POST), so the path is exactly /printshops/{printShopID}/employees. There is no class-level @RequestMapping to add any prefix, so the method-level value is the full path.
- The same exact path is also used by getEmployees (RequestMethod.GET) and editEmployee (RequestMethod.PUT), so GET, POST and PUT are explicitly supported for that path in the source code.
- DELETE is implemented only for /printshops/{printShopID}/employees/{employeeID} (it includes the employeeID path variable), so DELETE does not apply to the base path /printshops/{printShopID}/employees.
- HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE and PATCH are not present as explicit @RequestMapping method declarations in the code; per the instruction to base decisions on the code (not on framework runtime behavior like automatic HEAD/OPTIONS handling), they are reported as not acceptable.
- "All HTTP methods acceptable" is false because the controller does not declare a mapping that accepts every method (e.g., RequestMethod.ALL).
